(5) I know what is involved in processing and refining vegetable oils. Between the caustic soda, the hydrocarbons used in extracting the oils from the crushed seeds, and the catalytic hydrogenation (if any) I am actually inclined to take my chances with a little butter rather than soybean oil or margarine. Olive Oil is actually not too bad as far as processing, at least if you buy Extra Virgin. But avoid the others. <br>
<br>
The basic process is as follows:<br>
<br>
(A) The soybeans/sunflowers/whatever are ground up.<br>
<br>
(B) The ground seeds are extracted with hot Hexane (a hydrocarbon found in gasoline).<br>
<br>
(C) The solid seeds are discarded and the hexane mixture, (containing dissolved oil, lecithin, protein, and a few nasty-tasting trace organics) is moved along for further processing.<br>
<br>
(D) Caustic Soda is added to the Hexane mixture, causing most of the Lecithin, protein, etc to curdle out in a nasty goo which is filtered out and discarded, along with a percentage of the oil.<br>
<br>
(E) The Hexane-Oil mix is filtered through decolorizing carbon (also known as activated charcoal) to remove any remaining bitter-tasting or dark-colored contaminants.<br>
<br>
(F) The oil is heated to boil off most of the Hexane, bottled, and sold. The Hexane vapor is captured, condensed, and used to extract a fresh batch of seeds.<br>
